I think there‚Äôs a bit of a cultural tendency to talk about parenting as though permissiveness is a solution to punitiveness or vice versa. And I think this is a false dichotomy and we need a better way to talk about Kids These Days.
So let me give you an example:

A few months ago I was in a brewery reading, as is my wont, and there was a toddler walking around interacting with things she found while her guardian followed her. The toddler picked up my book and started to walk off with it. Her guardian said, ‚Äúcan she play with it?‚Äù to me.

Now, I knew there was a zero percent chance my paperback was surviving a lap around a bar with a toddler, so I said no. Kid gave it back. No one was rude. No hard feelings. 
Now: I have literally no negative feelings about this lady. I saw her one time. I have no idea if she

had slept an hour and cringed herself into a backache realizing she‚Äôd asked a stranger to let her kid play with their novel in public. Or maybe she‚Äôs self absorbed and thought I was a bitch. I don‚Äôt care. 
The book is fine. Nothing happened.

But here‚Äôs the thing: I think a lot of people would hear that story and say ‚Äúwell that‚Äôs why you need to spank your kid, so they don‚Äôt go around picking up things that aren‚Äôt theirs! She is going to grow up to be entitled!‚Äù
But I don‚Äôt think that fixes anything.

Let‚Äôs say your two year old is in public. They pick up the centerpiece, a bottle of ketchup, and a lady‚Äôs book. You let them pick up the centerpiece, look really anxious when she picks up the ketchup, and hit her when she picks up the lady‚Äôs book.

I have a hard time believing the two year old learns more from that if you let her pick up all three. Does a two year old really know the difference between a centerpiece and a lady‚Äôs book? How? Or does this just seem like random chaotic consequences?

But that‚Äôs not a goal you can have for your kid in public- ‚Äúnot these three things.‚Äù For a little brain it has to feel hopelessly abstract. 
But I don‚Äôt think ‚Äúlonger leash, shorter leash‚Äù or ‚Äúharsh consequences less harsh consequences‚Äù really resolves that.

I think the issue is that we don‚Äôt really have a positive vision of what kids should be doing in public and so managing them in public is kind of fighting the wind. We know they shouldn‚Äôt run around, yell, break things, and depending who you ask, be on screens.
